Abstract¶

This study examines the population and migration dynamics of monarch butterflies (Danaus plexippus) predicated on milkweed populations (primary food source) and historic air temperature data. Leveraging species observation data from iNaturalist, this research investigates the relationships–both general and geospatial–between air temperature, milkweed populations, and monarch populations. The study faces limitations due to the tenuous reliability of the iNaturalist dataset thereby imposing sampling bias. Geospatial analyses uncover a statistically significant positive correlation between the butterfly and milkweed populations (Moran’s I: 0.1770, p<0.01). In regards to temperature, we discover a statistically significant negative correlation between monarchs and hot temperature areas (Moran’s I: -0.05, p<0.01), and positive correlation between monarchs and cold temperature areas (Moran’s I: 0.05, p<0.01). Time-series analyses uncover no significant correlation between monarch populations and air temperature but a statistically significant correlation between monarch and milkweed populations (SARIMAX: coef = 0.2631, p<0.002). Possible catalysts are discussed.

Research Question¶

Can aggregate air temperature and milkweed population data predict the migration patterns and population density of monarch butterflies over time?

Background and Prior Work¶

This brief literature review will examine prior work relating to the migration patterns of Monarch butterflies (Danaus plexippus) and possible catalysts. Our research seeks to elucidate factors that contribute to the migration patterns and population density of Monarch butterflies over time. Studies such as Lemoine (2015) suggest that climate change is likely to alter the breeding ground distributions of eastern migratory Monarchs via range expansion of Asclepias host plants, potentially affecting Monarch distributions due to changes in host plant availability and habitat sustainability 1. Continuing on the climate front, Cohen (2023) highlighted that Monarchs born under autumn-like conditions showed lower post-metabolic rates and greater flight efficiency compared to those born under summer-like conditions 2. This observation coupled with historic climate data could aid in determining causal factors for migration pattern anomalies present in the population data. Climate aside, Flockhart et al (2015) have demonstrated that habitat loss on breeding grounds due to agricultural practices has been identified as a significant factor driving population declines in Monarch butterflies 3. Monarch butterflies utilize milkweed in cornfields throughout their breeding season, Oberhauser et al (2001) suggests that due to per-plant densities being higher in agricultural habitats than nonagricultural habitats, coupled with the prevalence of agricultural land, most Monarchs produced in the upper Midwest originated from cornfields or another agricultural land 4. The researchers suggest that agricultural practices such as weed control and insecticide use could significantly impact Monarch populations due to the loss of milkweed habitats in the areas aforementioned. While the studies by Lemoine (2015) and Flockhart et al. (2015) offer significant insights into the impact of climate change and habitat loss on Monarch populations, there is a gap in our understanding of the relationship between climate events and migration timing; we seek to bridge this gap by employing statistical techniques and machine learning. Methods to track the migration patterns and population density follow.

Mehmood et al (2023) compiled a project to track Monarch butterfly migration patterns utilizing web scraping, data processing, mapping via Python, and a Google Cloud AutoML Image Classification Model5. With these methods the researchers aggregated Citizen Science data related to Monarch butterfly sightings and verified said sightings using machine learning. Similarly, our project will utilize Citizen Science coupled with observations from iNaturalist to refine the analysis of migration patterns. Monarch sighting and temperature data were categorized from 1997-2023 and plotted on a map of the US(link to map). Recent studies have suggested that Monarchs have experienced an alarming decline in population size due to a combination of deforestation, loss of native milkweed and nectar plants, and climate change. In a similar approach, Patel et al (2021) developed an open-source tool utilizing deep convolutional neural networks to track Monarch sightings 6. Mahr (2024) developed a visualization project in R that visualizes the annual migration patterns of Monarch butterflies using data from the Global Biodiversity Information Facility 7. This project showcases the movement patterns of Monarchs month-over-month providing a strong basis from which we may architect our code for similar migration analysis. By adapting these techniques, we aim to further our understanding of Monarch migration patterns about habitat and climate change. These studies make explicit the ability to track the migration patterns of Monarch butterflies synchronously with variables such as temperature and deforestation.

Our project aims to build upon the work of the aforementioned studies, employing machine learning techniques to accurately predict Monarch migration patterns in response to climate change, milkweed density, and other confounding variables that may be uncovered throughout the course of this research.

Hypothesis¶

H0: Historic aggregate air temperature and milkweed population data cannot predict the migration patterns and population density of Monarch butterflies in North America.

Ha1: Historic aggregate air temperature data can predict the migration patterns and population density of Monarch butterflies in North America.

Ha2: Milkweed population data can predict the migration patterns and population density of Monarch butterflies in North America.

Given the scope of the relevant literature and available datasets, we believe that we can produce a model that can effectively predict the migration patterns and population density of Monarch butterflies in North America. Considering that the reliable tracking of Monarch migration patterns has been demonstrated, we feel confident in predicting these patterns with the added factors of climate change and milkweed density.

  • Dataset #3
    • Dataset Name: Berkeley Earth Global Gridded Temperature Data: Global Monthly Land + Ocean Average Temperature with Air Temperatures at Sea Ice (Recommended; 1850 – Recent)
    • Link to the dataset: https://berkeleyearth.org/data/
    • Number of observations: 135302400
    • Number of variables: 4

The datasets from iNaturalist contain user-submitted observations of Monarch butterflies and milkweed plants. We queried the data to filter for observations that are only in North America from 2008-03-01 to 20204-02-01. The iNaturalist datasets contain many unnecessary variables (user_id, taxon, etc.) that we will likely drop, as we are mainly interested in the date observed, latitutude, and longitude of each observation for each species.

The dataset from Berkeley Earth contains average air temperatures across a latitude-longitude grid from 1850 to the present. The only variables are time, latitude, longitude, and temperature, all of which we will keep. It should be noted that the temperature is reported in degrees Celsius as anomolies relative to the January 1951-December 1980 average. A 30-year baseline period is standard for modeling climate change 11, and the global average air temperature during the 1951-1980 period was 14 degrees Celsius 12. Because this dataset has observations from around the globe over a large time frame, there will be many rows that are outside of North America and/or outside the date range that will be dropped.

Since we are modeling whether milkweed population data and historical climate data can predict the population of Monarch butterflies, we will create and assign regions based on the latitude and longitude values and group the data by month and region.

Temperature Dataset¶

This dataset required us to convert the 'time' column from its given format of fractional years to a datetime object. This required the writing of a separate function. In addition, many rows had to be filtered out because they were outside the date and coordinate range of our project. The latitude and longitude variables also had to be cast to float64 to match the type in the monarch_df and milkweed_df dataframes.

Cleaning dataset¶

In [37]:
# helper function to check if year is leap year
def is_leap(year):
    return (year % 4 == 0 and (year % 400 == 0 or year % 100 != 0))

# function to convert from fractional year to datetime object taking leap years into account
def convert_fractional_year(frac_year):
    if isinstance(frac_year, datetime):
        return frac_year
    year = int(frac_year)
    frac = frac_year - year
    if (year % 4):
        days_in_year = 366
    else:
        days_in_year = 365
    days_passed = int(days_in_year * frac)
    start_date = datetime(year, 1, 1)
    date = start_date + timedelta(days=days_passed)
    return date

# drop null rows
temperature_df = temperature_df.dropna()

# drop rows not in latitude-longitude range
min_lat = min(monarch_df['latitude'].min(), milkweed_df['latitude'].min())
max_lat = max(monarch_df['latitude'].max(), milkweed_df['latitude'].max())
min_long = min(monarch_df['longitude'].min(), milkweed_df['longitude'].min())
max_long = max(monarch_df['longitude'].max(), milkweed_df['longitude'].max())
temperature_df = temperature_df[(temperature_df['latitude'] >= min_lat) & (temperature_df['latitude'] <= max_lat)]
temperature_df = temperature_df[(temperature_df['longitude'] >= min_long) & (temperature_df['longitude'] <= max_long)]

# convert time from fractional year to YYYY-MM-DD format
temperature_df['time'] = temperature_df['time'].apply(convert_fractional_year)

# drop rows not in date range
start_date = min(monarch_df['time'].min(), milkweed_df['time'].min())
end_date = max(monarch_df['time'].max(), milkweed_df['time'].max())
temperature_df = temperature_df[(temperature_df['time'] >= start_date) & (temperature_df['time'] <= end_date)]

# change latitude and longitude value types to float64
temperature_df[['latitude', 'longitude']] = temperature_df[['latitude', 'longitude']].astype(float)

Merging data¶

To create the final dataframe, we wanted to create a region column. Rather than make the region based off of state/province, we decided to choose the region with K-means clustering (note: the number of clusters that will be used is undecided and may be adjusted in the future). We then grouped the temperature, milkweed, and monarch data by month and region. We also created a new column which is the actual temperature in degrees Celsius, rather than the temperature measured as anomolies relative to the baseline period.

K-means clustering¶

In [38]:
# combine all latitude and longitude data from dataframes
coordinates = np.vstack((
    temperature_df[['latitude', 'longitude']].values,
    milkweed_df[['latitude', 'longitude']].values,
    monarch_df[['latitude', 'longitude']].values))

# perform K-means clustering
num_clusters = 50
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=num_clusters, random_state=42)
kmeans.fit(coordinates)

# assign clusters as regions back to each dataframe
temperature_df['region'] = kmeans.predict(temperature_df[['latitude', 'longitude']].astype(float))
milkweed_df['region'] = kmeans.predict(milkweed_df[['latitude', 'longitude']])
monarch_df['region'] = kmeans.predict(monarch_df[['latitude', 'longitude']])

# aggregate temperature data on a monthly basis by region
temperature_monthly_avg = temperature_df.groupby(['region', pd.Grouper(key='time', freq='M')]).temperature.mean().reset_index()

# aggregate milkweed presence on a monthly basis by region
milkweed_count = milkweed_df.groupby(['region', pd.Grouper(key='time', freq='M')]).size().reset_index(name='milkweed_count')

# aggregate monarch counts on a monthly basis by region
monarch_monthly_counts = monarch_df.groupby(['region', pd.Grouper(key='time', freq='M')]).size().reset_index(name='monarch_count')

# merge aggregated temperature and milkweed presence on region and time
features_df = pd.merge(temperature_monthly_avg, milkweed_count, on=['region', 'time'], how='outer').fillna({'presence': 0})

# merge the above with monarch counts to include monarch population data
final_df = pd.merge(features_df, monarch_monthly_counts, on=['region', 'time'], how='left').fillna({'monarch_count': 0})

# drop null rows
final_df = final_df.dropna()

# create new column called actual_temperature which is the temperature as an anomoly plus the baseline average
baseline_temperature = 14
final_df['actual_temperature'] = final_df['temperature'] + baseline_temperature

There is an interesting cyclic pattern to these data, and we can see that the number of observations across the board rises exponentially.

We can assume there would be some variation in observations because of seasonality. But it seems that there is another variable affecting the plot.

From Inaturalist we can see that the number of inaturalist users has risen in a similar way, and also the number of inaturalist observations as a whole behaves in a seasonal way2. We will keep this in mind for our analysis as a potential bias to the data.

Narrowing down to just one year (2023), We can see that milkweed observations preceed monarch observations.

Milkweeds are decideous, and do not have foliage during late fall and winter. They do bloom from June to August which can explain the spike in observations over that period9.

As far as Monarchs go, their abundance is a bit more complicated. However it does make sense to see more observations during the summer months as monarchs migrate from south America (and inland from the coast of California)10.

We will need to use spatial visualizations to see if our data shares this expected pattern.

    monarch_df[['latitude', 'longitude']].values))

model = LinearRegression()

# Dictionary to store the trends for each variable
trends = {}

# List of variables to analyze trends for
variables = ['temperature', 'milkweed_count', 'monarch_count', 'actual_temperature']

for variable in variables:
    # Reshape year for fitting the model
    X = final_df['year'].values.reshape(-1, 1)
    y = final_df[variable]
    
    # Fit the model
    model.fit(X, y)
    
    # Store the slope and intercept
    trends[variable] = {'slope': model.coef_[0], 'intercept': model.intercept_}

# Function to plot the trend
def plot_trend(df, variable, trend_info):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.scatter(df['year'], df[variable], label='Actual Data')
    plt.plot(df['year'], df['year'] * trend_info['slope'] + trend_info['intercept'],
             color='red', label='Trend Line')
    plt.title(f'Trend for {variable} over Years')
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel(variable)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# Now plot the trends for each variable
for variable in variables:
    plot_trend(final_df, variable, trends[variable])

From our data, we might infer that time has a notable effect on milkweed and monarch populations, this is not necessarily the case. See the discussion section for further analysis."

Final Analysis¶

Spatial Autocorrelation with Moran's I¶

Spatial autocorrelation can assess the degree of correlation between two spatial data sets. One way to measure this correlation is with a statistic known as Moran's I.

The Moran's I value ranges from -1 to 1:

Positive values indicate positive spatial autocorrelation (clustering of similar values)

Negative values indicate negative spatial autocorrelation (dispersion of dissimilar values)

A value near 0 suggests no spatial autocorrelation (random pattern)

Therefore a positive Moran's I should imply that our two variables are spatially correlated.

Milkweed vs Monarch Moran's I¶

In order to minimize confounding variables in the data, we need to first completely randomize the dataframe before merging.

If there is zero spatial correlation, then we expect a Moran's I value of 0.

The x-axis represents the relationship between our two variables, while the y-axis represents the average value of its neighbors for the same variable.

As seen in the graph, there seems to be a slight correlation as if Milkweeds and Monarchs had zero correlation the data points would be completely randomly dispersed.

We see that the Moran's I value is around 0.180 with a high confidence due to a small p-value of 0.001.

These results may imply that milkweed and butterfly have a detectable positive correlation.

In other words, the locations of milkweeds tend to be slightly associated with high local populations of monarch butterflies.

These findings coincide with the symbiotic relationship studied between monarchs and milkweeds as observed in our background research.

Cold vs Hot Temperatures Geospatial Analysis using Moran's I¶

Unlike Milkweed populations, temperatures have distinct values so they can't really be randomized to minimize confounding variables.

Instead, to better analyze how different temperatures are related to Monarch Populations, we can separate temperature into three buckets: cold, normal, and hot, then compare the Moran's I value for each bucket.

We expect there to be some inherent spatial correlation because of inherent observational biases in the dataset, so our main interest is the difference in spatial correlation between the temperature buckets. Our method to measure this is by first computing the Moran's I for all temperatures, then measuring the Moran's I difference from that baseline to get the "relative Moran's I" value.

Since temperature is generally normally distributed, lets use the standard deviation to split the buckets into:

Cold: 0.5 standard deviation below mean

Normal: 0.5 standard deviation within mean

Hot: 0.5 standard deviation above mean

By using a half standard deviation these buckets have evenly split sample sizes (~33% in each bucket).

In [53]:
#get mean, stdev
mean = sample_df_temp['temperature'].describe()['mean']
stdev = sample_df_temp['temperature'].describe()['std']

# Define temperature ranges for the buckets
cold_range = (sample_df_temp['temperature'] < mean-0.5*stdev)
normal_range = (sample_df_temp['temperature'] >= mean-0.5*stdev) & (sample_df_temp['temperature'] <= mean+0.5*stdev)
hot_range = (sample_df_temp['temperature'] > mean+0.5*stdev)

# Create three separate DataFrames for cold, normal, and hot temperatures
cold_df = sample_df_temp[cold_range]
normal_df = sample_df_temp[normal_range]
hot_df = sample_df_temp[hot_range]

We have too many dataframes now so lets create a function to generate the Moran's I more efficiently:

In [54]:
def generate_temp_morans(df,temp_bucket_name,baseline_morans):
    # Converting DataFrame to a GeoDataFrame
    gdf_temp = gpd.GeoDataFrame(df, geometry=gpd.points_from_xy(df.longitude_temp, df.latitude_temp))
    gdf_monarch = gpd.GeoDataFrame(df, geometry=gpd.points_from_xy(df.longitude_monarch, df.latitude_monarch))

    # Creating a spatial weights matrix
    w = weights.Queen.from_dataframe(gdf_temp,use_index=False)

    # Calculate Moran's I for monarch distance from milkweed
    distance_monarch_temp = gdf_temp.distance(gdf_monarch.geometry)
    moran_distance_monarch = esda.Moran(distance_monarch_temp, w)

    if(baseline_morans != 0):
        # Visualize Moran's I scatterplot for monarch distance from temperature
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))
        moran_scatterplot(moran_distance_monarch, ax=ax)
        # Set axis labels and title
        ax.set_xlabel(temp_bucket_name + " vs Monarch Distance")
        ax.set_ylabel(temp_bucket_name + " vs Monarch Spatially Lagged")
        ax.set_title(f'Spatial Autocorrelation of {temp_bucket_name} vs Monarchs (Relative Moran\'s I = {moran_distance_monarch.I-baseline_morans:.4f}; P-value: {moran_distance_monarch.p_sim:.4f})')

    return round(moran_distance_monarch.I,4)

Remember that there are inherent confounding variables in the data (observational biases, data is ordered by date) so we expected some inherent spatial correlation.

With that in mind we see that with all temperatures the baseline Moran's I is around 0.33.

Now we can compare how cold, normal, and hot global temperatures relate to monarch spatial correlation.

When temperatures are in a normal range, the relative spatial correlation is around 0.01.

When temperatures are colder, the relative spatial correlation is is around 0.05

When temperatures are one standard deviation colder, the relative spatial correlation is around -0.05.

From these results, we can conclude that in comparison to the entire temperature dataset, monarch butterflies are slightly more spatially correlated with colder temperatures, while monarch butterflies are slightly less spatially correlated with hotter temperatures.

These results imply that Monarch populations are more geospatially clustered to colder areas, while they are more geospatially distant to hotter areas, compared to their clustering around normal temperatures.

These findings generally coincide with the fact that Monarch populations are a cold-blooded species, so they would prefer to cluster around colder temperatured areas while avoiding hotter temperatured areas.

Time Series Analysis¶

For this analysis we wanted to conduct a time series analysis to model the correlation between both milkweed population and temperature against monarch count over time. We chose to use the SARIMAX (Seasonal Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average with eXogenous variables) model, which is used to model and forecast data that exhibit seasonal patterns and are influenced by external factors. In particular, we will be modeling milkweed_count vs monarch_count and temperature vs monarch_count.

Create sarimax_df¶

To get the data in a format usable for SARIMAX analysis, we must modify the final dataframe slightly. First we grouped the temperature, milkweed counts, and monarch counts by month. We then adjusted the temperature column to reflect the actual temperature rather than the anomoloy from baseline. Finally, we filtered the date range based on what we observed in the EDA and set the time as the index.

In [59]:
# aggregate temperature data on a monthly basis by region
temperature_monthly_avg = temperature_df.groupby([pd.Grouper(key='time', freq='M')]).temperature.mean().reset_index()

# aggregate milkweed counts on a monthly basis by region
milkweed_presence = milkweed_df.groupby([pd.Grouper(key='time', freq='M')]).size().reset_index(name='milkweed_count')

# aggregate monarch counts on a monthly basis by region
monarch_monthly_counts = monarch_df.groupby([pd.Grouper(key='time', freq='M')]).size().reset_index(name='monarch_count')

# merge aggregated temperature and milkweed counts on region and time
features_df = pd.merge(temperature_monthly_avg, milkweed_presence, on=['time'], how='outer').fillna({'presence': 0})

# merge the above with monarch counts to include monarch population data
sarimax_df = pd.merge(features_df, monarch_monthly_counts, on=['time'], how='left').fillna({'monarch_count': 0})

# drop null rows
sarimax_df = sarimax_df.dropna()

# adjust temperature column which is the temperature as an anomoly plus the baseline average
baseline_temperature = 14
sarimax_df['temperature'] = sarimax_df['temperature'] + baseline_temperature

# filter dates
start_date = pd.to_datetime('2019-01-01')
end_date = pd.to_datetime('2023-12-17')
sarimax_df = sarimax_df[(sarimax_df['time'] >= start_date) & (sarimax_df['time'] <= end_date)]

# set time as index
sarimax_df.set_index('time', inplace=True)

Milkweed vs Monarch with SARIMAX¶

Using auto_arima from the pdarima package, we fit a SARIMAX model to the milkweed_count column and the monarch_count column. The benefit of using auto_arima is it automatically detects the optimal parameters for an ARIMA model. We set the seasonal parameter equal to true to account for the seasonality of monarch populations, and we set the m parameter equal to 12 to indicate monthly data with an annual seasonal cycle.

In [61]:
y = sarimax_df['monarch_count']
X = sarimax_df['milkweed_count']

model = auto_arima(y, X=X.values.reshape(-1,1), seasonal=True, m=12, stepwise=True, suppress_warnings=True)
print(model.summary())

Ethics & Privacy¶

In the context of our project, three primary concerns have been identified: the prevalence of data in densely populated regions, the limitation of data collection to regions of North America, and the reliance on data from only two sources. Acknowledging and addressing these concerns is crucial to ensure the ethical conduct of our research, prevent biases, and foster equitable outcomes.

One significant concern revolves around the overrepresentation of observations in densely populated regions, potentially introducing biases that may not accurately reflect Monarch butterfly behaviors in less urbanized areas. Additionally, data stored from these sources may include people’s username as well as other personal information, but by filtering out these details we mitigate privacy concerns. Another concern involves the limitation of data collection to specific regions in North America, raising questions about the global applicability of our model and potential exclusion of diverse migration patterns from other continents. While in some cases this limitation could incur a sampling error/bias, considering Monarch’s are primarily found throughout North America, we do not anticipate it to skew any analysis we make from said data. The third concern revolves around relying on data from only two sources, posing the risk of introducing biases specific to those datasets and limiting the model's comprehensiveness.

By acknowledging and proactively addressing these concerns, our project endeavors to uphold ethical standards and contribute to a more equitable and well-rounded exploration of butterfly migration patterns.

Discusison and Conclusion¶

Revisit of Background and Prior Work¶

Previous studies have highlighted the potential impact of climate change and habitat loss on the migration patterns and population density of monarch butterflies. Factors such as changes in breeding ground distributions, variations in flight efficiency due to climate conditions, and loss of milkweed habitats have been identified as potential drivers of monarch population declines. Our research aimed to highlight the relationship between historic climate data, milkweed population data, and the migration patterns of monarchs, building upon the foundational work of researchers like Lemoine (2015), Cohen (2023), and Flockhart et al. (2015).

Revisit of Hypotheses¶

H0: Historic aggregate air temperature and milkweed population data cannot predict the migration patterns and population density of Monarch butterflies in North America.

Ha1: Historic aggregate air temperature data can predict the migration patterns and population density of Monarch butterflies in North America.

Ha2: Milkweed population data can predict the migration patterns and population density of Monarch butterflies in North America.

Regarding Ha1, spatial autocorrelation results suggest a weak association between air temperature (both hot and cold) and monarch observations. With Morans I's of -0.05 (hot) and 0.05 (cold)--both at the .01 significance level--we thereby sustain the null. The same can be said for Ha2 with Moran's I of 0.1770 at the .01 significance level. Furthermore, time series analyses uncover no signiciant correlation between monarch populations and air temperature but uncover a statistically significant relationship between monarch and milkweed populations (SARIMAX: coef = 0.2631, p<0.002). We do not however have confidence to accept Ha2 as will be discussed in the following subsection.

Limitations of the iNaturalist Data¶

While the iNaturalist dataset provided a valuable source of citizen science observations for monarch butterflies and milkweed plants, several limitations hindered our ability to establish a concrete connection between migration patterns and climate factors. Firstly, the data's reliability and completeness were uncertain due to the nature of citizen science contributions, potentially introducing biases and inconsistencies. Secondly, the temporal and spatial coverage of the observations was not sufficient to capture the full extent of monarch migration patterns across North America. Additionally, the available variables and metadata in the iNaturalist dataset were limited, lacking crucial information about environmental conditions and other factors that could influence migration.
The shape of all iNaturalist data as such–that is, all species observations on iNaturalist–closely mirrors the shape of both the milkweed and monarch data; compare the Figures below:

13

It is readily apparent that sampling error is present, likely contributing to the poor accuracy of our models, moreover supposing an inaccurate representation of milkweed and monarch populations. As to the possible reasons for the inordinate shape of the iNaturalist data, two are most prescient: (1) Referring back to the figures, between the years of 2008 and 2019 the number of observations is low; we then see an increase in observations by an order of magnitude in 2018 and onward. This likely attributed in part to the proliferation of technology, and access thereof, affording for better measurement tools and lowering the ceiling for those engaging in citizen science. Furthermore, the shape of the distribution is also attributed in part to the increase in popularity of the iNaturalist platform as such–which is ostensibly synchronized with the aforementioned technology boom. (2) Regarding human behavior, we see a decrease in iNaturalist observation during the latter portions of each calendar year and a corresponding increase near the middle portions (this is conjecture but for the sake of brevity, Q4 and Q1 for the former, Q2 and Q3 for the latter). This is likely attributed to poor weather conditions, inhibiting to-be observers from going outside and making observations. That is, we see increased observations during the summer months with a corresponding decrease in the winter months due to weather conditions.

Lessons Learned and Future Directions¶

This research experience underscored the importance of reliable and high-quality data for ecological and climate-related studies. By combining multiple data sources and techniques, we may overcome the limitations faced in this study and gain a more comprehensive understanding of monarch migration patterns.

Concluding Remarks¶

The culmination of our project has highlighted the ongoing importance of understanding the intricate relationships between species' migration, climate change, and habitat availability. By learning from the limitations faced in this study, we can pave the way for more impactful research that informs conservation strategies and mitigates the effects of environmental changes on vulnerable populations such as that of the Monarch Butterfly.
